<paragraph blockId="1.[151,1437,320,1247]" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">
In erecting this genus, Priesner described two new species from Java and Sumatra, although both are now considered synonyms of 
<taxonomicName box="[354,426,356,382]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Physothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lefroyi">
<emphasis box="[354,426,356,382]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">lefroyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. This 
<typeStatus box="[495,543,357,383]" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">type</typeStatus>
species differs from the other known species in the genus in having ocellar setae pair III very small (
<figureCitation box="[371,439,392,419]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-137@3.[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Lefroyothrips species. Antennal segments, 1–6: (1) fasciatus holotype; (2) fasciatus male; (3) lefroyi; (4) pictus paratype; (5) tribulationi; (6) varatharajani. 7–8 lefroyi: (7) female; (8) head &amp; pronotum. L. tribulationi, 9–10: (9) head; (10) pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543157" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543157/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">Fig. 8</figureCitation>
), in having the postocular setae arranged in an irregular pair of rows not in a single row, and in having the metascutum strongly reticulate (
<figureCitation box="[722,807,428,455]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1463,1487]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,452,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[151,1435,452,1439]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Lefroyothrips species—metascutum. (11) fasciatus holotype; (12) fasciatus paratype male; (13) fasciatus male; (14) lefroyi; (15) tribulationi; (16) varatharajani." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543159/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">Fig. 14</figureCitation>
). All of the known males in the genus have a set of six thorn-like setae on tergite IX (
<figureCitation box="[490,620,464,491]" captionStart="FIGURES 17–23" captionStartId="6.[151,264,1956,1980]" captionTargetBox="[152,1436,453,1932]" captionTargetId="figure-157@6.[152,1436,453,1933]" captionTargetPageId="6" captionText="FIGURES 17–23. Lefroyothrips species. Female tergites VII–X, 17–19: (17) lefroyi; (18) pictus; (19) tribulationi. male tergite IX, 20–21: (20) pictus; (21) fasciatus. (22) lefroyi female sternites VI–VII. (23) fasciatus fore wing." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543161" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543161/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">Figs 20–21</figureCitation>
, 
<figureCitation box="[631,662,464,491]" captionStart="FIGURES 24–27" captionStartId="7.[151,264,808,832]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetId="figure-17@7.[151,1435,181,783]" captionTargetPageId="7" captionText="FIGURES 24–27. Lefroyothrips species. L. varatharajani 24–26: (24) head; (25) male tergites VIII–IX; (26) male sternites. (27) L. lefroyi male sternites." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543163" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543163/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">25</figureCitation>
), but the male sternites bear pore plates in three species although not in two species (male not known for 
<taxonomicName authority="Mound &amp; Ng, 2021" authorityName="Mound &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2021" box="[557,685,500,526]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Lefroyothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tribulationi" status="sp.n.">
<emphasis box="[557,685,500,526]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">tribulationi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[692,746,501,527]" pageId="1" pageNumber="568" rank="species">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[692,741,501,527]" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">sp.n</emphasis>
.
</taxonomicNameLabel>
). Further remarkable differences among the included species are in the fore wing banding pattern, as indicated in the key below, in the presence of additional setae medially on the metascutum of two species, 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Moulton" baseAuthorityYear="1940" box="[512,643,573,599]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Lefroyothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="fasciatus">
<emphasis box="[512,643,573,599]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">L. fasciatus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Mound &amp; Ng" authorityYear="2021" box="[698,857,572,598]" class="Insecta" family="Thripidae" genus="Lefroyothrips" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" order="Thysanoptera" pageId="1" pageNumber="568" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="tribulationi">
<emphasis box="[698,857,572,598]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">L. tribulationi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
(
<figureCitation box="[872,1043,572,599]" captionStart="FIGURES 11–16" captionStartId="5.[151,264,1463,1487]" captionTargetBox="[155,1432,452,1439]" captionTargetId="figure-125@5.[151,1435,452,1439]" captionTargetPageId="5" captionText="FIGURES 11–16. Lefroyothrips species—metascutum. (11) fasciatus holotype; (12) fasciatus paratype male; (13) fasciatus male; (14) lefroyi; (15) tribulationi; (16) varatharajani." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543159" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543159/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">Figs 11–12, 15</figureCitation>
), in the form of antennal segments III–IV (
<figureCitation box="[237,338,608,635]" captionStart="FIGURES 1–10" captionStartId="3.[151,264,1932,1956]" captionTargetBox="[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetId="figure-137@3.[151,1435,417,1909]" captionTargetPageId="3" captionText="FIGURES 1–10. Lefroyothrips species. Antennal segments, 1–6: (1) fasciatus holotype; (2) fasciatus male; (3) lefroyi; (4) pictus paratype; (5) tribulationi; (6) varatharajani. 7–8 lefroyi: (7) female; (8) head &amp; pronotum. L. tribulationi, 9–10: (9) head; (10) pronotum." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4543157" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4543157/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="568">Figs 1–6</figureCitation>
), and in the length of ocellar setae pair III from 15 to 80 microns.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
